{"id": 7879, "date": "2019-03-20T05:00:00", "date_gmt": "2019-03-20T12:00:00", "guid": {"rendered": "http://estreetshuffle.com/?p=7879"}, "modified": "2019-03-20T05:44:33", "modified_gmt": "2019-03-20T12:44:33", "slug": "cover-me-the-winter-blanket-darkness-on-the-edge-of-town", "status": "publish", "type": "post", "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/2019/03/20/cover-me-the-winter-blanket-darkness-on-the-edge-of-town/", "title": {"rendered": "Cover Me, The Winter Blanket: Darkness on the Edge of Town"}, "content": {"rendered": "<p>On one level, this cover has no business working as well as it does.</p>\n<p>&#8220;<a href=\"http://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/2018/04/10/roll-of-the-dice-darkness-on-the-edge-of-town/\">Darkness on the Edge of Town</a>&#8221; is an angry song&#8211;anger born out of frustration.</p>\n<p>But if we listen to Bruce&#8217;s lyrics carefully, we realize that while Bruce sings &#8220;Darkness&#8221; in a tone of determination and defiance, at its core it&#8217;s a song of addiction and defeat.</p>\n<p>Midwest band The Winter Blanket gets it. Their cover taps into the isolation and resignation of the point-of-view character and reinvents the song as one of quiet contemplation and acceptance of one&#8217;s lot in life.</p>\n<p>The result is a delicate, introspective recasting of one of Bruce&#8217;s most well-known songs, by a band that clearly understands and honors Bruce&#8217;s songwriting.</p>\n<p>Take a listen:</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"Darkness On The Edge Of Town\" width=\"758\" height=\"569\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/WLKkQiI56Qo?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n", "protected": false}, "excerpt": {"rendered": "<p>The Winter Blanket gives us a quiet, introspecti